      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-08-06T23:03:32Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Honestly, I still doesn\u0027t quite get the best practice in GO about when to return error and when to panic. But\n\n\u003e when returning an error is easy, ie you don\u0027t need to propagate it through layers and layers of otherwise clean algorithmic functions, just return it. At call site, it\u0027d be easier to log additional details.\n\nMakes sense to me.\n\n\u003e and to remain succinct in tests, use helper to assert error:\n\u003e   run :\u003d func(...) []cls{\n\u003e     res, err :\u003d Optimize(...)\n\u003e     if err !\u003d nil {panic(err)}  \n\u003e     return res\n\u003e   }\n\u003e \n\u003e \n\u003e (I use panic in helpers instead of So(err, ShouldBeNil) to get full stack in GoConvey Web UI instead of useless line number)\n\nDone",
